.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[3]\*(C'\fR contains the discriminant \f(CWd(K)\fR (\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.disc\*(C'\fR) of \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[4]\*(C'\fR contains the index of \fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR,
i.e.\ \f(CW\*(C`[\*(C'\fR\fBZ\fR\f(CW\*(C`_K : \*(C'\fR\fBZ\fR\f(CW\*(C`[\*(C'\fR\fItheta\fR\f(CW\*(C`]]\*(C'\fR, where \fItheta\fR is any root of \fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[5]\*(C'\fR is a vector containing 7 matrices \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`MC\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`T2\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`T\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`MD\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`TI\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`MDI\*(C'\fR useful for certain computations in the number field \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR is the \f(CW\*(C`(r1+r2) x n\*(C'\fR matrix whose columns represent
the numerical values of the conjugates of the elements of the integral
basis.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR \f(CW\*(C`MC\*(C'\fR is essentially the conjugate of the transpose of \f(CW\*(C`M\*(C'\fR,
except that the last \f(CW\*(C`r2\*(C'\fR columns are also multiplied by 2.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR \f(CW\*(C`T2\*(C'\fR is an \f(CW\*(C`n x n\*(C'\fR matrix equal to the real part of the
product \f(CW\*(C`MC.M\*(C'\fR (which is a real positive definite symmetric matrix), the
so-called \f(CW\*(C`T_2\*(C'\fR\-matrix (\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.t2\*(C'\fR).
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR \f(CW\*(C`T\*(C'\fR is the \f(CW\*(C`n x n\*(C'\fR matrix whose coefficients are
\&\f(CW\*(C`Tr(\*(C'\fR\fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_i\*(C'\fR\fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_j)\*(C'\fR where the \fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_i\*(C'\fR are the elements of the
integral basis. Note that \f(CW\*(C`T = \eoverline{MC}.M\*(C'\fR and in particular that
\&\f(CW\*(C`T = T_2\*(C'\fR if the field is totally real (in practice \f(CW\*(C`T_2\*(C'\fR will have real
approximate entries and \f(CW\*(C`T\*(C'\fR will have integer entries). Note also that
 \fIdet\fR \f(CW\*(C`(T)\*(C'\fR is equal to the discriminant of the field \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR The columns of \f(CW\*(C`MD\*(C'\fR (\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.diff\*(C'\fR) express a \fBZ\fR\-basis
of the different of \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR on the integral basis.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR \f(CW\*(C`TI\*(C'\fR is equal to \f(CW\*(C`d(K)T^{\-1}\*(C'\fR, which has integral
coefficients. Note that, understood as as ideal, the matrix \f(CW\*(C`T^{\-1}\*(C'\fR
generates the codifferent ideal.
.PP
\&\ \ \fB*\fR Finally, \f(CW\*(C`MDI\*(C'\fR is a two-element representation (for faster
ideal product) of \f(CWd(K)\fR times the codifferent ideal
(\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.disc*\*(C'\fR\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.codiff\*(C'\fR, which is an integral ideal). \f(CW\*(C`MDI\*(C'\fR
is only used in \f(CW\*(C`idealinv\*(C'\fR.
.IX Xref "idealinv"
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[6]\*(C'\fR is the vector containing the \f(CW\*(C`r1+r2\*(C'\fR roots
(\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.roots\*(C'\fR) of \fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR corresponding to the \f(CW\*(C`r1+r2\*(C'\fR
embeddings of the number field into \fBC\fR (the first \f(CW\*(C`r1\*(C'\fR components are real,
the next \f(CW\*(C`r2\*(C'\fR have positive imaginary part).
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[7]\*(C'\fR is an integral basis in Hermite normal form for \fBZ\fR\f(CW\*(C`_K\*(C'\fR
(\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.zk\*(C'\fR) expressed on the powers of\ \fItheta\fR.
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[8]\*(C'\fR is the \f(CW\*(C`n x n\*(C'\fR integral matrix expressing the power
basis in terms of the integral basis, and finally
.PP
\&\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[9]\*(C'\fR is the \f(CW\*(C`n x n^2\*(C'\fR matrix giving the multiplication table
of the integral basis.
.PP
