.ie n .SS "rnfinit""(""\fInf\fP"",""\fIpol\fP"")"""
.el .SS "rnfinit\f(CW(\fP\fInf\fP\f(CW,\fP\fIpol\fP\f(CW)\fP"
.IX Xref "rnfinit"
.IX Subsection "rnfinit(nf,pol)"
\&\fInf\fR being a number field in
\&\f(CW\*(C`nfinit\*(C'\fR
format considered as base field, and \fIpol\fR a polynomial defining a relative
extension over \fInf\fR, this computes all the necessary data to work in the
relative extension. The main variable of \fIpol\fR must be of higher priority
(i.e.\ lower number) than that of \fInf\fR, and the coefficients of \fIpol\fR
must be in \fInf\fR.
.PP
The result is an 11\-component row vector as follows (most of the components
are technical), the numbering being very close to that of \f(CW\*(C`nfinit\*(C'\fR. In
the following description, we let \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR be the base field defined by
\&\fInf\fR, \f(CW\*(C`m\*(C'\fR the degree of the base field, \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR the relative degree, \f(CW\*(C`L\*(C'\fR
the large field (of relative degree \f(CW\*(C`n\*(C'\fR or absolute degree \f(CW\*(C`nm\*(C'\fR), \f(CW\*(C`r_1\*(C'\fR and
\&\f(CW\*(C`r_2\*(C'\fR the number of real and complex places of \f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR contains the relative polynomial \fIpol\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[2]\*(C'\fR is a row vector with \f(CW\*(C`r_1+r_2\*(C'\fR entries, entry \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR being
a 2\-component row vector \f(CW\*(C`[r_{j,1},r_{j,2}]\*(C'\fR where \f(CW\*(C`r_{j,1}\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`r_{j,2}\*(C'\fR
are the number of real and complex places of \f(CW\*(C`L\*(C'\fR above the \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th place of
\&\f(CW\*(C`K\*(C'\fR so that \f(CW\*(C`r_{j,1} = 0\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`r_{j,2} = n\*(C'\fR if \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR is a complex place, while if
\&\f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR is a real place we have \f(CW\*(C`r_{j,1}+2r_{j,2} = n\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[3]\*(C'\fR is a two-component row vector \f(CW\*(C`[\*(C'\fR\fBd\fR\f(CW\*(C`(L/K),s]\*(C'\fR where \fBd\fR\f(CW\*(C`(L/K)\*(C'\fR
is the relative ideal discriminant of \f(CW\*(C`L/K\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`s\*(C'\fR is the discriminant of
\&\f(CW\*(C`L/K\*(C'\fR viewed as an element of \f(CW\*(C`K^*/(K^*)^2\*(C'\fR, in other words it is the output
of \f(CW\*(C`rnfdisc\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[4]\*(C'\fR is the ideal index \fBf\fR, i.e.\ such that
\&\f(CW\*(C`d(pol)\*(C'\fR\fBZ\fR\f(CW\*(C`_K = \*(C'\fR\fBf\fR\f(CW\*(C`^2\*(C'\fR\fBd\fR\f(CW\*(C`(L/K)\*(C'\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[5]\*(C'\fR is a vector \fIvm\fR with 7 entries useful for certain
computations in the relative extension \f(CW\*(C`L/K\*(C'\fR. \fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR is a vector of
\&\f(CW\*(C`r_1+r_2\*(C'\fR matrices, the \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th matrix being an \f(CW\*(C`(r_{1,j}+r_{2,j}) x n\*(C'\fR
matrix \f(CW\*(C`M_j\*(C'\fR representing the numerical values of the conjugates of the
\&\f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th embedding of the elements of the integral basis, where \f(CW\*(C`r_{i,j}\*(C'\fR is as
in \fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[2]\*(C'\fR. \fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[2]\*(C'\fR is a vector of \f(CW\*(C`r_1+r_2\*(C'\fR matrices, the
\&\f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th matrix \f(CW\*(C`MC_j\*(C'\fR being essentially the conjugate of the matrix \f(CW\*(C`M_j\*(C'\fR
except that the last \f(CW\*(C`r_{2,j}\*(C'\fR columns are also multiplied by 2.
\&\fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[3]\*(C'\fR is a vector of \f(CW\*(C`r_1+r_2\*(C'\fR matrices \f(CW\*(C`T2_j\*(C'\fR, where \f(CW\*(C`T2_j\*(C'\fR is
an \f(CW\*(C`n x n\*(C'\fR matrix equal to the real part of the product \f(CW\*(C`MC_j.M_j\*(C'\fR
(which is a real positive definite matrix). \fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[4]\*(C'\fR is the \f(CW\*(C`n x n\*(C'\fR
matrix \f(CW\*(C`T\*(C'\fR whose entries are the relative traces of \fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_i\*(C'\fR\fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_j\*(C'\fR
expressed as polmods in \fInf\fR, where the \fIomega\fR\f(CW\*(C`_i\*(C'\fR are the elements
of the relative integral basis. Note that the \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th embedding of \f(CW\*(C`T\*(C'\fR is
equal to \f(CW\*(C`\eoverline{MC_j}.M_j\*(C'\fR, and in particular will be equal to
\&\f(CW\*(C`T2_j\*(C'\fR if \f(CW\*(C`r_{2,j} = 0\*(C'\fR. Note also that the relative ideal discriminant of
\&\f(CW\*(C`L/K\*(C'\fR is equal to  \fIdet\fR \f(CW\*(C`(T)\*(C'\fR times the square of the product of the ideals
in the relative pseudo-basis (in \fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[7][2]\*(C'\fR). The last 3 entries
\&\fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[5]\*(C'\fR, \fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[6]\*(C'\fR and \fIvm\fR\f(CW\*(C`[7]\*(C'\fR are linked to the different
as in \f(CW\*(C`nfinit\*(C'\fR, but have not yet been implemented.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[6]\*(C'\fR is a row vector with \f(CW\*(C`r_1+r_2\*(C'\fR entries, the \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th entry
being the
row vector with \f(CW\*(C`r_{1,j}+r_{2,j}\*(C'\fR entries of the roots of the \f(CW\*(C`j\*(C'\fR\-th embedding
of the relative polynomial \fIpol\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[7]\*(C'\fR is a two-component row vector, where the first component is
the relative integral pseudo basis expressed as polynomials (in the variable of
\&\f(CW\*(C`pol\*(C'\fR) with polmod coefficients in \fInf\fR, and the second component is the
ideal list of the pseudobasis in \s-1HNF\s0.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[8]\*(C'\fR is the inverse matrix of the integral basis matrix, with
coefficients polmods in \fInf\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[9]\*(C'\fR may be the multiplication table of the integral basis, but
is not implemented at present.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[10]\*(C'\fR is \fInf\fR.
.PP
\&\fIrnf\fR\f(CW\*(C`[11]\*(C'\fR is a vector \fIvabs\fR with 5 entries describing the
\&\fIabsolute\fR extension \f(CW\*(C`L/\*(C'\fR\fBQ\fR. \fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR is an absolute equation.
\&\fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[2]\*(C'\fR expresses the generator \fIalpha\fR of the number field
\&\fInf\fR as a polynomial modulo the absolute equation \fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[1]\*(C'\fR.
\&\fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[3]\*(C'\fR is a small integer \f(CW\*(C`k\*(C'\fR such that, if \fIbeta\fR is an abstract
root of \fIpol\fR and \fIalpha\fR the generator of \fInf\fR, the generator
whose root is \fIvabs\fR will be \fIbeta\fR\f(CW\*(C` + k \*(C'\fR\fIalpha\fR. Note that one must
be very careful if \f(CW\*(C`k ! = 0\*(C'\fR when dealing simultaneously with absolute and
relative quantities since the generator chosen for the absolute extension
is not the same as for the relative one. If this happens, one can of course
go on working, but we strongly advise to change the relative polynomial so
that its root will be \fIbeta\fR\f(CW\*(C` + k \*(C'\fR\fIalpha\fR. Typically, the \s-1GP\s0 instruction would
be
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`pol = subst(pol, x, x \- k*Mod(y,\*(C'\fR\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`.pol))\*(C'\fR
.PP
Finally, \fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[4]\*(C'\fR is the absolute integral basis of \f(CW\*(C`L\*(C'\fR expressed in \s-1HNF\s0
(hence as would be output by \f(CW\*(C`nfinit(vabs[1])\*(C'\fR), and \fIvabs\fR\f(CW\*(C`[5]\*(C'\fR the
inverse matrix of the integral basis, allowing to go from polmod to integral
basis representation.
.PP
The library syntax is \fBrnfinitalg\fR\f(CW\*(C`(\*(C'\fR\fInf\fR\f(CW\*(C`,\*(C'\fR\fIpol\fR\f(CW\*(C`,\*(C'\fR\fIprec\fR\f(CW\*(C`)\*(C'\fR.
.IX Xref "rnfinitalg"
